sec.p:
Underlying the carer–relative relationship is the issue of communication which is increasingly challenged through the course of the disease. This is not related simply to language difficulty asdemonstrated by forgetfulness and word-finding problems, or difficulties arising from impaired memory which might lead to confusion. Communication can break down when existing relationship boundaries and characteristics become changed, for example when customary behaviour is replaced by something else, perhaps more bizarre, which renders the carer confused and afraid through misunderstanding. It is necessary to acknowledge the impression such an impact makes during day-to-day contact between the carer and the person being cared for. In this study difficulties with communication were reported by nearly all of the carers and affected the quantity and quality of day-to-day conversation including:


increasing withdrawal such as seemingly having less to say or a reluctance to instigate conversation;

repetition of questions leading to repeated reminders by carer;

inability to find answers leading to repeated ‘testing’ by carer;

getting things wrong leading to repeated correction by carer;

inability to remember names of family and seen as insensitive and perplexing;

interpreting behaviour change as indicative of personality change;

behaviour that seemed to imply increasing lethargy such as diminished interest in personal care and in reading and watching TV;

selfish behaviour based on apparent lack of interest in the welfare of others;

illogical behaviour and conversation, perplexing to carer;

disturbed behaviour and language, distressing to carer.
